1	\chapter{The symmetric monoidal category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules}
2	\label{chap:Modules_Monoidal}
3	
4	This chapter opens Phase~C by introducing the symmetric monoidal structure on the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules for a scheme $X$. It is a prerequisite for Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}: the definition of a \emph{line bundle} as an invertible object requires a monoidal category to invert in. Mathlib provides the structure on the presheaf side (\texttt{PresheafOfModules.monoidalCategory}) and the sheafification machinery (\texttt{PresheafOfModules.sheafification}); the gap addressed here is the transfer of the monoidal structure across sheafification to the sheaf side, yielding an instance \texttt{MonoidalCategory $X$.Modules}.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supplying the Mathlib-gap-fill that unblocks the refinement of $\mathrm{LineBundle}$ from a global-sections approximation to the geometric definition.
7	
8	\section{Setup}
9	
10	Fix a scheme $X$. Recall (Chapter~\ref{chap:Cohomology_StructureSheafAb}) that $\mathcal O_X$-modules are organised as a category $X.\mathrm{Modules}$, packaged as $\mathrm{SheafOfModules}(\mathcal O_X)$ where $\mathcal O_X$ is regarded as a sheaf of (commutative) rings on the underlying topological space of $X$. The presheaf-of-modules variant $\mathrm{PresheafOfModules}(\mathcal O_X)$ already carries a symmetric monoidal structure in Mathlib (\texttt{PresheafOfModules.monoidalCategory}), with tensor product computed pointwise on each open: for two presheaves of modules $M, N$,
11	\[
12	  (M \otimes_{\mathcal O_X} N)(U) \;=\; M(U) \otimes_{\mathcal O_X(U)} N(U).
13	\]
14	The associator, unitors, and braiding are inherited pointwise from $\mathrm{ModuleCat}\,\mathcal O_X(U)$.
15	
16	\section{Tensor product of sheaves of modules}
17	
18	\begin{definition}[Tensor product of $\mathcal O_X$-modules]
19	  \label{def:Modules_tensorObj}
20	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Modules.tensorObj}
21	  Let $X$ be a scheme and $M, N \in X.\mathrm{Modules}$. The \emph{tensor product} $M \otimes_{\mathcal O_X} N$ is defined as the sheafification of the presheaf tensor product:
22	  \[
23	    M \otimes_{\mathcal O_X} N \;:=\; \mathrm{sheafify}\bigl(M_{\mathrm{psh}} \otimes_{\mathcal O_X, \mathrm{psh}} N_{\mathrm{psh}}\bigr),
24	  \]
25	  where $(-)_{\mathrm{psh}}$ is the forgetful functor $X.\mathrm{Modules} \to \mathrm{PresheafOfModules}\,\mathcal O_X$, and the inner tensor product is the pointwise one supplied by Mathlib.
26	\end{definition}
27	
28	\begin{remark}
29	  When $X$ is affine, both factors are quasi-coherent and the presheaf tensor product is already a sheaf on the basis of basic opens, so the sheafification step collapses to an isomorphism; but for a general scheme $X$ (and a general pair of $\mathcal O_X$-modules) the presheaf tensor product is genuinely not a sheaf and sheafification is essential.
30	\end{remark}
31	
32	\begin{theorem}[Symmetric monoidal structure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$]
33	  \label{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}
34	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Modules.instMonoidalCategory}
35	  \uses{def:Modules_tensorObj}
36	  For every scheme $X$, the category $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ carries a canonical symmetric monoidal structure with tensor product given by Definition~\ref{def:Modules_tensorObj} and tensor unit $\mathcal O_X$ itself (as the trivial $\mathcal O_X$-module).
37	\end{theorem}
38	
39	\begin{proof}
40	  \uses{def:Modules_tensorObj}
41	  The presheaf-of-modules category has a symmetric monoidal structure with pointwise tensor product. The associator, unitors, and braiding satisfy the pentagon, triangle, and hexagon axioms pointwise. Sheafification is left adjoint to the inclusion of sheaves into presheaves and is symmetric monoidal: tensor commutes with colimits, and sheafification is the left Kan extension along the inclusion of covering sieves, so the universal property transfers the monoidal structure to the sheaf side. Concretely, the associator/unitors/braiding on the sheaf side are sheafifications of their presheaf counterparts, and the coherence axioms are inherited from the presheaf side via the universal property.
42	\end{proof}
43	
44	\begin{remark}[Mathlib precedent]
45	  Mathlib has the same pattern at one level of abstraction higher: \texttt{CategoryTheory.Sheaf.monoidalCategory} lifts a symmetric monoidal structure from a value category $A$ to $\mathrm{Sheaf}\,J\,A$ provided $J.W$ is monoidal and $A$ has weak sheafification ($J.W$-isomorphisms are detected pointwise after sheafification). The condensed case (\texttt{LightCondensed.instMonoidalCategorySheafLightProfiniteCoherentTopologyModuleCat}) shows this pattern in action. The wrinkle in our situation is that the value category varies with the open set (we have a sheaf of rings, not a fixed ring), so the generic instance \texttt{Sheaf.monoidalCategory} does not apply directly --- instead we need a parallel construction adapted to the presheaf-of-modules formalism. The proof is bookkeeping rather than mathematics.
46	\end{remark}
47	
48	\section{Invertible objects and line bundles}
49	
50	\begin{definition}[Invertible $\mathcal O_X$-module]
51	  \label{def:Modules_Invertible}
52	  An $\mathcal O_X$-module $L$ is \emph{invertible} (or a \emph{line bundle}) if there exists $L' \in X.\mathrm{Modules}$ and an isomorphism $L \otimes_{\mathcal O_X} L' \cong \mathcal O_X$.
53	\end{definition}
54	
55	Equivalently, $L$ is invertible iff it is an invertible object of the symmetric monoidal category $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ in the sense of \texttt{CategoryTheory.MonoidalCategory.Invertible}.
56	
57	This is the substrate that Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle} is supposed to use to define $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$. The current chapter (still using the global-sections approximation $\mathrm{CommRing.Pic}\,\Gamma(X, \top)$) is forward-compatible with this refinement; the refinement is the content of Phase~C step~C1 (see \texttt{STRATEGY.md}).
58	
59	\section{Mathlib gap}
60	
61	Mathlib provides:
62	\begin{itemize}
63	  \item \texttt{PresheafOfModules.monoidalCategory} on the presheaf side (\texttt{Mathlib/Algebra/Category/ModuleCat/Presheaf/Monoidal.lean}).
64	  \item \texttt{PresheafOfModules.sheafification} (\texttt{Mathlib/Algebra/Category/ModuleCat/Presheaf/Sheafification.lean}) and \texttt{SheafOfModules.toSheafCompSheafToPresheafIso} as the comparison data.
65	  \item The generic \texttt{CategoryTheory.Sheaf.monoidalCategory} pattern for fixed-value monoidal categories.
66	\end{itemize}
67	
68	What is \emph{missing} and supplied by this chapter:
69	\begin{itemize}
70	  \item The instance \texttt{MonoidalCategory $X$.Modules} for $X$ a scheme. This is bookkeeping work over the existing presheaf-side instance.
71	  \item The invertibility predicate (Definition~\ref{def:Modules_Invertible}) and its API.
72	\end{itemize}
73	
74	\section{Use in the project}
75	
76	Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory} unblocks:
77	\begin{itemize}
78	  \item Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}, step~C1 of Phase~C: redefining $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ as the type of invertible $\mathcal O_X$-modules (instead of the global-sections approximation).
79	  \item Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}, step~C2: the relative Picard functor reformulated on the corrected $\mathrm{LineBundle}$.
80	  \item Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_Functor}, step~C3: the representability theorem (FGA-style or via symmetric powers) is honestly stateable only after this refinement.
81	\end{itemize}
82	
83	\section{Formalization status}
84	
85	The Lean-side scaffolding lives in \texttt{AlgebraicJacobian/Modules/Monoidal.lean} and carries the three signatures \texttt{Scheme.Modules.tensorObj}, \texttt{Scheme.Modules.instMonoidalCategoryStruct}, and \texttt{Scheme.Modules.instMonoidalCategory}. The bodies are filled across successive prover rounds: the file is the active target of Phase~C step~C0 in the project strategy.
